<DOC><DOCNO> AP880915-0057 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-15-88 0350EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-15 0513</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,470</SECOND><HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD><HEAD>U.S. Says Libya Able To Produce Chemical Weapons</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department says an intelligencereport that Libya is on the verge of producing chemical weapons is``a particularly worrisome development'' in light of Libya's recordof state-sponsored terrorism.   Department spokesman Charles Redman on Wednesday called onnations that may be contributing to the Libyan program to halttheir aid. He said the kinds of materials used in chemical weaponsare available on the world market.   Redman said the United States verified the alleged Libyanactivities only recently, but he provided no information on type ofweapons Libya is developing nor did he say how U.S. officialslearned of the operations.   Redman noted that there were reports last year that Libya hadused chemical weapons in its war with Chad.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Senate Panel Insists North Comply With 5-Month-Old Subpoena</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee isinsisting that fired White House aide Oliver L. North producehundreds of pages of classified diary pages the former Marinelieutenant colonel has so far kept from the panel.   The committee voted 11-8 on Wednesday to insist North complywith a subpoena it issued five months ago.   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., is seeking the full diaries for asubcommittee investigating international narcotics traffickingbecause of heavily censored references to narcotics he noticed incopies of diaries obtained by the Iran-Contra committees.   North, through his attorney Brendan L. Sullivan, has objected toturning over the voluminous diaries. Kerry urged his colleagues topursue the papers, saying ``delay plays into the hands ... of thosewho want to see all of this disappear.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>House, Senate Agree On Compromise Military Construction Spending</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Congress has approved $8.8 billion in spendingfor military construction projects in the year beginning Oct. 1.   The appropriation came in separate votes hours apart Wednesday,first in the House and then in the Senate, that sent the compromisemeasure to President Reagan for his signature.   The House-Senate agreement is an increase from the $8.3 billionconstruction budget for the current fiscal year but is below the$9.7 billion sought by Reagan.   It includes $65 million for the final stage of construction of anational test facility in Colorado for Reagan's Strategic DefenseInitiative, also known as Star Wars. Absent, however, is $31million Reagan had sought for construction of a railroad-basedversion of the MX nuclear-tipped missile.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Mail to Great Britain Still Halted</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Postal Service is still askingAmericans to withhold mail to Great Britain, even though mailworkers in that country have settled their strike.   Mail to Britain was embargoed last week because of the strike,and U.S. officials said they would return Britain-bound items tothe senders.   Although an agreement to settle the strike was reached Monday, ahuge backlog of mail remains to be sorted and delivered there. U.S.officials said Wednesday it may be at least a week before theybegin accepting mail addressed to the United Kingdom.</TEXT></DOC>